<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-939-290  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 939 290.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  Dec 4 1989 n277 p18(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Client-server to be rage?andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gibson, Stanley.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Analysts predict that the client-server architecture will be thebasis of future computing systems.andP;  This growth will be dependenton the development of database management and applicationssoftware.andP;  Recent studies conclude that distributed databases willgrow 100 percent between now and 1993, becoming a multibilliondollar market.andP;  In key vertical markets such as finance, bankingand insurance, there are currently 630,000 database systems inuse, of which 8,350 are client-server databases and only 25 aretrue distributed databases.andP;  By 1993, these figures will havechanged to 63,000 client-server systems and 1,600 distributeddatabases.andP;  An ideal distributed database would be able to operateon any vendor's hardware, using any vendor's database managementsystem and any application.andP;  Before this happens, standardscovering protocols, and communications for distributed databaseswill have to be developed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Client/Server ArchitectureData Base Management SystemsInformation Storage and RetrievalDistributed ProcessingGrowthVertical Market.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   How distributed database use will grow. (graph)What kind of databases are being used. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>